&X000001 = L I.5 Erra and Išum SB I
#project: eblo
#atf: lang akk-x-stdbab
#atf: use unicode
#atf: use math
#atf: use legacy

#tr.en: King of all settlements, creator of the universe, […]!
1. %n šar (|) gimir (|) dadmē | bānû (|) kibrā[ti (|) ... ]
#note: The interpretation of the opening lines of the poem is a @i{vexata quaestio}. The most serious difficulty is the identification of the character described as “king of all settlements,” who could conceivably be Išum, Erra, or even Marduk (see already @bib{RN31@135-137}). It seems easiest to interpret that the poem begins with a hymn to Išum, as defended by @bib{mueller1995wer@349-360}, @bib{RN1593@48-49}, and @bib{RN455@60-61}, among others. @bib{RN31@138} assumed that the missing portion of the line contained “un terzo epiteto divino, composto di due o tre elementi, che dia al verso lo stesso ritmo ternario dei vv. 3-5.” @bib{RN675@263}, who is of the opinion that the opening lines are addressed to Erra, restores [@i{qurādu Erra}], “[warrior Erra].”
// L 0.0 NA "-" b+1
HuzNA1 i 1. [LU]GAL gi-mir da-ad₂-me ba-nu#-u# kib#-[ra-a-ti x x x (x x x)]
BabLB3 i 1. [x] gi-mir da-ad₂-me ba-nu-u₂ kib-ra-a#-[ti x x x (x x x)]

#tr.en: Hendursanga, first-born son of Enlil, [...],
2. %n hendursanga | apil (|) ellil | rēšt[û | ... ]
HuzNA1 i 2. {d}hendur-sag-ga₂ IBILA {d}+en-lil₂ reš-t[u-u₂ x x x (x x x)]
BabLB3 i 2. [{d}hen]dur-sag-ga₂ IBILA {d#}+en#-lil₂# reš-tu#-[u₂ x x x (x x x)]

#tr.en: Bearer of the august scepter, shepherd of the black-headed people, herdsman of [@i{mankind}]!
3. %n nāš (|) haṭṭi | ṣīrti | nāqid (|) ṣalmāt (|) qaqqadi | rēʾû | [tenēšēti?]
#note: As noted by @bib{RN83@22 fn. 3}, the entire line contains an etymographic interpretation of the name Hendursaĝa (i.e. Išum): @akk{GA₂} = @i{nāš}, @akk{PA} = @i{ḫaṭṭu}, @akk{SAG} = @i{ṣīrtu}, @akk{PA.<|DAG.KISIM₅×KAK|>} = @i{nāqid}, @akk{SAG GA₂} =  @akk{GE₂₆} (for @akk{GE₆}) = @i{ṣalmāt qaqqadi}, @akk{PA.<UDU>} = @i{rēʾû} (see also @bib{RN3058@6a} and @bib{RN1593@66 fn. 7}). The free restoration @i{tenēšēti} at the end follows @bib{temp_id_07390035038145881@200} (see also @bib{RN31@140}).
AššNA2 i 1'. [x x x x ṣi]r-ti na!?(NU)-q[id!?] ṣal!?#-[mat SAG].DU# re-ʾu-u!? [x x x x x]
HuzNA1 i 3. na-aš₂ haṭ-ṭu ṣir-ti na-qid ṣal-mat q[aq-qa-di x x x (x x)]
BabLB3 i 3. [n]a-aš₂# haṭ-ṭi# ṣir-ti na#-qid# ṣal#-mat# SAG.D[U x x x (x x)]

#tr.en: Išum, zealous butcher whose hands are suited to bear his fierce weapons,
4. %n īšum | ṭābihu | naʾdu | ša ana našê (|) kakkīšu | ezzūti | qātāšu | asmā
#note: As first noted by @bib{RN706@400} (see also @bib{RN31@140} and @bib{RN1593@66 fn. 7}), @i{ṭābihu naʾdu} is an etymographic interpretation of the name of Išum. The line is cited in an inscription of Assurbanipal (see @bib{RN661@192-193} and @i{apud} @bib{RN54@157 l. 22}).
AššNA2 i 2'. [x x x ṭa]-bi-hu na-aʾ-du ša₂ ana na#-še*#-e*# {giš#}TUKUL#-MEŠ-šu₂ ez-zu#-ti# ŠU+MIN-šu₂ as#-ma
#note: Collation of the line in Lambert’s folio 18397.
HuzNA1 i 4. {d}i-šum ṭa₂(TA)-bi-hu na-aʾ-du ša₂ ana n[a-še-e x x x x x x x]
#note: According to @bib{RN31@140 fn. 11}, the sign @akk{TA} is used for @akk{ṭa₂} only in this line in all manuscripts of the Epic.
BabLB3 i 4. {d#}i#-šum ṭa-bi-hu na#-aʾ#-du ša₂ ana na-š[e-e x x x x x x x]

#tr.en: And at the lightning of whose wrathful spears even Erra, the warrior of the gods, trembles in (his) abode!
5. %n (u) ana šubruq (|) ulmīšu | šērūti | erra | qarrād (|) ilī | inūšu | ina šubti
#note: Most modern interpreters take @i{inūšu} as a subordinative in the relative clause started in l. 4 (see @bib{RN1593@66 fn. 6} with further bibliographical references, and also @bib{RN455@61 fn. 66}). The line is cited in the narrative of Sargon’s Eighth Campaign, as noted by @bib{RN282@127 fn. 52}.
AššNA2 i 3'. u₃ ana šub-ruq# ul-me-šu₂ še#-ru-ti {d}er₃-ra qar-rad DINGIR-MEŠ i-nu-šu₂*# ina šub-ti
#note: Collation of the line in Lambert’s folio 18397.
HuzNA1 i 5. ana šub-ruq ul-me-šu₂ še-ru-ti {d}er₃-ra q[ar-rad x x x x x x x x]
BabLB1a i 1'. [x šub-ru]q? u[l?-me-šu₂ x x x x x x x x x x x x x x x x]
BabLB3 i 5. [a-n]a š[u]b-ruq ul-me#-šu₂# še-ru-tu# {d}er₃-ra# [x x x x x x x x x x]

#tr.en: His heart yearned for combat;
6. %n īrissū-ma | libbašu || epēš (|) tāhāzi
#note: Compare the description of the passage 6-14 in @bib{RN1593@49-50}: “The poet follows the five-line invocation by showing Išum (and the audience) a scene in which Išum’s master, lying in bed, ponders the pros and cons of going to war. The arguments are articulated as an internal dialogue between Erra’s mind (@i{libbu}, literally ‘heart’) and his physical self.”
AššNA2 i 4'. e-ri-su-ma lib₃-ba-šu₂ e-peš ta-ha-zi
HuzNA1 i 6. i-ris-su-ma lib₃-ba-šu₂ & e-pe[š x x x]
BabLB1a i 2'. i#-ri#-iš#-su-m[a x x x x x x x x]
BabLB3 i 6. [i-ri-iš-s]u-ma# lib₃-ba-šu₂# e-pe[š x x x]

#tr.en: To his weapons he exhorted, “Smear yourselves with deadly venom!”
7. %n ītammi | ana kakkīšu || litpatā | imat (|) mūti
AššNA2 i 5'. i-ta-ma ana {giš}TUKUL-MEŠ-šu₂ lit-pa-ta i-mat mu-u-ti
HuzNA1 i 7. i-ta-mi a-na {giš}TUKUL-MEŠ-šu₂ & lit-[pa-ta x x x x x]
BabLB1a i 3'. i#-ta-me a-na# [x x x x x x x x x x x x]
BabLB3 i 7. [x x x] a#-na kak-ki-šu₂ lit#-p[a-ta x x x x x]

#tr.en: To the Seven, peerless warriors, “Gird your arms!”
8. %n ana sebetti | qarrād (|) lā šanān || nandiqā | kakkīkun
AššNA2 i 6'. a-na {d}IMIN-BI qar-rad la ša₂-na-an na-an-di-qa kak-ki#-ku-un
HuzNA1 i 8. ana {d}IMIN-BI qar-rad la ša₂-na-an & na-a[n-di-qa x x x x]
BabLB1a i 4'. ana {d}IMIN-BI qa[r-rad x x x x x x x x x x x x]
BabLB3 i 8. [x x {d}IMIN-B]I qar#-rad# la# ša₂#-na#-[an x x x x x x x x]
