#tr.en: And he said to you, (Išum): “I shall head for the (battle) field!”
9. %n iqabbīku | ana kâša || luṣī-ma | ana ṣēri
AššNA2 i 7'. i-qab-bi-ku a-na ka-a-ša₂ lu-ṣi-ma a-na EDIN
HuzNA1 i 9. i-qab-bi-ma a-na ka-ša₂ & lu-[ṣi-ma x x]
BabLB1a i 5'. i-qab-bi-ma# [x x x x x x x x x x x]

#tr.en: You alone are the torch, it is your light they look to!
10. %n attā | dipārum-ma || inaṭṭalū | nūrka
#note: Compare @bib{RN3058@4a}: “Earlier in the poem of Erra and Išum, Erra’s heart explicitly identifies Išum as @i{diparu}, “a firebrand,” that the gods follow into battle (I 10). From this it follows that the light which the night watchmen Išum and Ḫendursanga shone to lead people home at night was a burning torch or firebrand. Indeed, it seems likely that Išum’s divine power was instantiated in the fiery glow of the torch, and that his name was indeed the masculine form of the Akkadian common noun @i{išātum}, “fire.””
// cf. L III.4 38
AššNA2 i 8'. at-ta di-pa-ru-um-ma i-na-aṭ-ṭa-lu nu-ur₂-ka#
HuzNA1 i 10. at-ta di-pa-ru-um-ma i-na-ṭ[a-lu x x x]
BabLB1a i 6'. at-ta di-pa-ru#-u[m-ma x x x x x x x x]

#tr.en: You alone are the champion, the gods [@i{march behind}!]
11. %n attā | ālik (|) mahrim-ma || ilū (|) ... [ ... ]
AššNA2 i 9'. at-ta a-lik mah#-ri-im-ma & DINGIR-MEŠ x [x x x (x)]
