#tr.en: Should Erra arise, when he destroys the country,
13. %n erra | tebī-ma || ina sapān (|) māti
#note: The line has been almost universally interpreted as a command from Išum to Erra, an interpretation that results in awkward syntax and makes the introduction impossibly difficult to understand. Compare: @bib{RN31@59}: “Erra, alzati! Nell’abbattere il paese”; @bib{RN447@117}: “Debout donc, Era! A terrasser le pays”; @bib{cagni1977poem@84}: “Arise, Erra! By laying waste the country”; @bib{bottero1977antiquites@113} and @bib{RN39@682}: “Debout, Erra! Quant tu saccageras la terre”; @bib{RN216@285} and @bib{dalley1997erra@405}: “O Erra, rise up, and in overwhelming the land”; @bib{polentz1989eigenbegrifflichkeit@23}: “Erra, erheb dich! Wie wird beim Niedermachen des Landes”; @bib{RN712@783}: “Erra, erhebe dich, und beim Einebnen des Landes”; @bib{RN675@264}: “Erra, erhebe dich! (…) beim Niederwalzen des Landes”; @bib{RN1593@50}: “O Erra, arise! (…) when laying the land low!”; @bib{taylor2017erra@336}: “Erra, arise, and in crushing the land”. Note, however, that two MSS (AššNA2 and BabLB1a) have a clear stative @i{tebī-ma}, whereas only the Sultantepe MS, whose readings are generally inferior to those of the others, has an apparent imperative @akk{ti-be₂-ma}. The only interpreter who tried to translate the manuscripts’ stative was @bib{RN1811@92}: “Ist Era erhoben beim Niederstrecken des Landes”. In our view, it is a conditional sentence (see the note on the next line).
AššNA2 i 11'. {d}er₃-ra te-b[i]-ma# & ina sa-pan ma-a-ti#
HuzNA1 i 13. {d}er₃-ra ti-be₂-ma & i#-[na sa-pa]n [x x x]
BabLB1a i 9'. {d}er₃-ra te-bi-m[a x x x x x x x]

#tr.en: Your mind will not rejoice, your heart will not be joyous.
14. %n kī namrat | kabtatka || (u) hadû | libbuk
#note: As noted by @bib{RN31@143-144}, this is the first line in the Epic in which sentence boundary does not coincide with verse boundary. The @i{plene} writing of @i{ḫadû} shows that @i{kī} cannot be an interrogative adverb, as traditionally interpreted (“wie wird da strahlen dein Gemüt und erfreut sein dein Herz!” in @bib{mueller1995wer@350}; “How your mood will be bright, your heart joyous!” in @bib{RN1593@50}); but rather a conjunction introducing an oath formula (“If your mind rejoices and your heart is joyous (…)”, i.e., “your mind will surely not be happy, nor your heart be joyous”).
AššNA2 i 12'. ki-i nam-rat# kab-ta-at-ka u₃ ha-du-u lib-bu-uk
HuzNA1 i 14. ki#-i nam-rat kab-ta-[k]a!? & [h]a-[d]u-u₂ l[ib₃-bu-uk]
BabLB1a i 10'. ki-i nam-rat [x x x x x x x x x x]

#tr.en: Erra, like a sleepless man, his limbs are weary,
15. %n erra | kī ša amēli | dalpi || idāšu | an[hā]
AššNA2 i 13'. {d}er₃-ra ki-i ša₂ a-me-li dal-pi i-da-a-šu₂ an-[ha]
HuzNA1 i 15. [{d}e]r₃-ra ki-i ša₂ a-me₂-li# dal#-pi# i-da#-a-šu₂ [x x]
BabLB1a i 11'. {d}er₃-ra ki#-i ša₂ L[U₂? x x x x x x x x]

#tr.en: To his heart he said: “Shall I arise? Or shall I sleep on?”
16. %n iqabbi | ana libbīšu || lutbe | luṣlal-ma
AššNA2 i 14'. i-qab-bi a-na lib₃-bi-šu₂ & lu-ut-be₂ lu-uṣ#-lal-ma
HuzNA1 i 16. [i-qab-b]i a-na lib₃-bi-šu₂# & lu-ut-be₂# lu-uṣ-l[al-ma]
BabLB1a i 12'. i-qab-bi a-na lib#-b[i-šu₂ x x x x x x x]

#tr.en: To his weapons he exhorted, “Keep leaning on the corners!”
17. %n ītamma | ana kakkīšu || ummedā | tubqāti
// cf. L I.12 SB "-" 164
AššNA2 i 15'. i-ta-a-ma a-na kak-ki-šu₂ & um-me-da tub#-qa-a-ti
HuzNA1 i 17. i#-ta#-[mi x x {giš}TUKUL-M]EŠ-šu₂ & um-me-da tub₂-qa-a#-[ti]
BabLB1a i 13'. i-ta-ma a#-[na x x x x x x x x x x]

#tr.en: To the Seven, peerless warriors, “Return to your abode!”.
18. %n ana sebetti | qarrād (|) lā šanān || ana šubtīkunu | tūrā-ma
