#tr.en: Together with Mami, his wife, he revels.
20. %n itti māmi | hīratuš || ippuša | ulṣam-ma
AššNA2 i 18'. it-ti {d}ma-mi hi#-ra-tuš & ip-pu-ša₂ ul-ṣa-am-ma
HuzNA1 i 20. [i]t-ti {d}ma-ma hi#-r[a]-tuš & ip-pu-šu₂ ul-ṣa#-am-ma

#tr.en: O Engidudu, lord who wanders in the night, who guides the princes,
21. %n engidudu | bēlu | muttallik (|) mūši | muttarrû (|) rubê
#note: As has been repeatedly noted, both @i{muttallik mūši} and @i{muttarrû rubê} are etymographic translations of the name Engidudu: see @bib{RN31@149}, @bib{NABU1989-3@1989/3}, and @bib{RN3058@3-4}.
AššNA2 i 19'. {d}+en-gi₆-du-du# be#-lu₄*# mut*#-tal*#-lik*# mu#-ši mu[t]-tar#-ru-u ru-be₂-e
#note: Collation of the line in Lambert’s folio 18397.
HuzNA1 i 21. [{d}+en]-gi₆-du-du EN mut-tal#-lik# GE₆# mut-tar-ru-u₂ NUN-MEŠ

#tr.en: Who leads safely lad and girl, illuminating (them) like the light of day!
22. %n ša eṭla (|) u ardata | (ina šulmi) | ittanarrû | unammaru | kīma ūmi
#note: As seen by most intepreters, @i{namāru} D must be transitive: compare e.g. “Che il giovane e la fanciulla guida sempre in (buona) salute e (li) rende splendidi come (la luce del) giorno” (@bib{RN31@61}, courtesy E. Tadmor).
AššNA2 i 20'. ša₂ eṭ-la u ar-da-tu it-ta-na#-ru-u u₂-nam-ma*#-ru GIM u₄-me
HuzNA1 i 22. [x] GURUŠ u {munus}KI.SIKIL ina šul#-[m]u i!?#-[t]a-nar-ru-u₂ u₂-nam#-ma-ru GIM u₄-mi

#tr.en: The divinity of the Seven, peerless warriors, is quite another:
