#tr.en: Whoever looks at them is paralyzed with fear: their breath is death,
25. %n āmiršunu | uštahhat-ma || napīssunu | mūtum-ma
AššNA2 i 23'. [a]-mir-šu₂-nu uš-tah-ha-at na-pi-is-su-nu mu-tum₃#-ma!?#
HuzNA1 i 25. a#-mir-šu₂-nu uš-tah-hat-ma & na-pis-su-nu mu#-tum₃-ma

#tr.en: People are terrified and dare not approach it.
26. %n nišū | šahtū-ma || ul iʾirrū | ana šâšu
#note: “It” (@i{šâšu}) may refer either to the “breath” (so @bib{RN31@151} and @bib{cagni1977poem@27 n. 9}) or else to the Seven, considered as a unit (so @bib{RN1811@72}). As noted by @bib{RN31@151}, @i{nišū} here and elsewhere in the Epic (e.g. ll. 41, 73) is a masculine noun (on @i{nišū} as a masculine noun, see also @bib{RN2725@377 fn. 5}).
AššNA2 i 24'. UN-MEŠ šah₂-tu*#-ma# & ul ir-ru a-na ša₂-a-šu
#note: Collation of the line in Lambert’s folio 18397.
