#tr.en: He summoned the first and gave him orders:
31. %n issī-ma | ištēn || išakkana | ṭēma
#note: @bib{RN31@152-153} links the functions of the Seven as presented in ll. 31-38 with the destructive actions described elsewhere in the Epic, mostly assumed by Erra.
AššNA2 i 29'. is-si-ma iš-ten₂ i-šak-ka-[na ṭe₃]-e-ma
HuzNA1 i 31. is#-si-ma# DIŠ#-en i-šak-ka-na ṭ[e₃]-e#-mu

#tr.en: “Wherever you go in your rage — you shall have no rival!”
32. %n ēma (|) tandirū-ma | tattalku || māhira | ē tarši
AššNA2 i 30'. e-ma*# ta-an-nam#-ru-ma ta-at-tal#-ku ma-hi-r[a] e!?# [ta]r!?-ši
#note: Collation of the line in Lambert’s folio 18397.
HuzNA1 i 32. [e]-ma [ta-a]n-di-ru-ma ta!?#-tal-ku ma-hi#-ra# e# [t]ar-ši
#note: The reading @akk{ta!?#} instead of @akk{i} (as copied) follows @bib{RN31@61}, but needs collation.

#tr.en: He said to the second: “Burn like fire and blaze like a flame!”
33. %n iqabbi | ana šanî | kīma gīri | kubum-ma || humuṭ | kīma nabli
AššNA2 i 31'. i-qab-bi ana ša₂-ne₂-e GIM {d}gira₂* gu-b[u-u]m-[ma h]u-muṭ# GIM# nab-li₃
#note: Collation of the line in Lambert’s folio 18397.
HuzNA1 i 33. i-qa[b-bi x] MIN-i GIM {d#}gira₂# ku-bu-um-ma# hu-muṭ GI[M n]ab-li

#tr.en: He exhorted the third: “Let your face be that of a lion so that whoever beholds you melts down!”
34. %n ītammi | ana šalši | zīm (|) labbi | lū šaknātā-ma | āmirka | lišharmiṭ
// cf. L I.5 SB "III" 124
// cf. L I.5 SB "IV" 21
// cf. L I.2 SB "I" 139
// cf. L I.2 SB "II" 25
// cf. L I.2 SB "III" 2
// cf. L I.2 SB "III" 128
NinNA1b i 1'. [x x x x x zi-i]m? lab#-bi# [x x x x x x x x x x x x x]
AššNA2 i 32'. i*-tam?*#-ma# ana šal-ši zi-im lab-bi lu*# šak*#-na*#-ta-ma a-me-ru*-uk*# liš*#-har-miṭ
#note: According to @bib{RN31@154 fn. 40}, collation of the line does not yield any satisfactory result because the tablet has deteriorated greatly at this point. In any case, as noted by Cagni, the signs copied (@akk{DU₃-uš#-ma}) cannot be right. Compare, however, the collation of the line in Lambert’s folio 18397, followed here.
HuzNA1 i 34. i-t[a-mi an]a šal-ši z[i]-im la-bi lu šak-na#-[t]a-ma a-mir-ka [li]š-har-miṭ

#tr.en: He said to the fourth: “May the mountain be destroyed at the attack of your fiery weapons!”
35. %n iqabbi | ana rebî | ana našê (|) kakkīka | ezzūti | šadû | lītabbit
NinNA1b i 2'. i#-qab#-bi# ana# LIMMU#-i# ana* ni-iš {giš#}TU[KUL-MEŠ-ka] ez?#-z[u?-ti x x x x x]
#note: Collation of Lambert @i{apud} @bib{RN31@Fig. 14}.
AššNA2 i 33'. i-qab-bi ana re-be₂-e ana na*#-še*#-e {giš*}TUKUL*#-MEŠ-ka ez-zu-ti KUR-u li-tab#-bit#
#note: Collation of the line in Lambert’s folio 18397.
HuzNA1 i 35. i-qab#-[bi x r]e-bi-i a-na na-še-e {giš}TUKUL-MEŠ#-[k]a ez-[z]u-ti KUR-u₂ li#-tab*#-bit
#note: Collation in @bib{RN728@92}.

#tr.en: And then to the fifth he said: “Blow like the wind and overwhelm the world!”
36. %n ana hamši | iqtabi | kīma šāri | zīq-ma || kippata | hīṭa
#note: In some contexts the verb @i{ḫâṭu} is used together with @i{zâqu}, occasionally as synonyms, as noted in @bib{RN1853@109-113}. The translation adopted follows @bib{RN608@42-46} (see also @bib{RN1853@110 fn. 221}).
NinNA1b i 3'. a#-na# IA₂# iq#-ta#-bi ki-ma# IM# zi#-qi₂-i[m] k[ip]-pa-ta hi-i#-ṭu*
#note: Collation of Lambert @i{apud} @bib{RN31@Fig. 14}.
AššNA2 i 34'. a-na ha-an-ši iq-ta-bi GIM IM# zi#-iq*#-ma ki[p*-p]a*-ta hi-i-ṭa
#note: Collation of the line in Lambert’s folio 18397.
HuzNA1 i 36. a-na [ha-am]-ši# iq-ta-bi GIM IM ziq#-ma# kip-pat hi-iṭ-ṭa#

#tr.en: To the sixth he commanded: “sweep over above and below, sparing no one!”
37. %n šešša | umtaʾʾer | eliš (|) u šapliš | bāʾam-ma || lā tagammil | mamma
NinNA1b i 4'. AŠ₃#-šu₂ [u]m-ta*#-ʾi-ir# e-liš u šap#-liš ba-ʾa-[a]m-ma la*# ta-gam-mil mam-ma
#note: Collation of Lambert @i{apud} @bib{RN31@Fig. 14}.
AššNA2 i 35'. šeš-ša₂ um-ta-ʾi-ir e-liš u šap-liš ba-ʾa-ma [l]a tag-gam-mil mim-ma
HuzNA1 i 37. [š]eš-[ša₂ u]m-ta-ʾi-ir e-liš u# šap#-liš ba-ʾa-ma la ta-gam-mil mam-ma

#tr.en: The seventh he filled with viper’s venom: “Finish (all) life!”.
38. %n sibâ | imat (|) bašmi | iṣēnšū-ma | šumqita | napišta
NinNA1b i 5'. IMIN#-a# i*#-mat*# ba#-aš₂#-me# i#-ṣi-in-šu#-ma# š[u]m*-qi₂#-ta ZI-ta
#note: Collation of Lambert @i{apud} @bib{RN31@Fig. 14}.
AššNA2 i 36'. se-ba-a i-mat ba-aš₂-me i-ṣe-en-šu₂-ma šum-qi₂-ta na#-[p]iš-tu
HuzNA1 i 38. ša-ba#-a i-mat ba-aš₂-mi i-[ṣ]e*-en-šum-ma u₂-šam-qat ZI-t[i₃]
#note: Collation in @bib{RN728@92}.

#tr.en: Once Anu had fixed the lot of all Seven,
39. %n ultu (|) šīmat (|) sebetti | napharšunu || išīmu | ānu
NinNA1b i 6'. ul*#-tu*# ši-mat {d}IMIN-BI nap#-har#-šu₂-nu i-šim#-mu {d}a-num
#note: Collation of Lambert @i{apud} @bib{RN31@Fig. 14}.
AššNA2 i 37'. [ul-t]u₂ ši-mat {d}IMIN-BI nap-har-šu₂-nu i-ši-mu {d}a-num
HuzNA1 i 39. ul-tu# ši#-mat {d}IMIN-BI nap#-har-šu₂-nu i-ši-mu {d}a-num

#tr.en: He handed them over to Erra, the warrior of the gods, (saying): “Let them march at your flank!
40. %n iddinšunūtī-ma | ana erra | qarrād (|) ilī || lillikū | idāka
#note: The repetition of the phrase @i{lillikū idāka} in ll. 40 and 44 is described as an “enveloping figure” by @bib{RN554@174}.
NinNA1b i 7'. id#-din#-šu#-nu-ti#-ma ana {d}er₃#-ra qar-rad DINGIR-[MEŠ l]il-li-ku i-da-ka
#note: Collation of Lambert @i{apud} @bib{RN31@Fig. 14}.
AššNA2 i 38'. [id-din]-šu₂#-nu-ti-ma ana {d}er₃-ra qar-rad DINGIR-MEŠ lil-li-ku i-da-ka
HuzNA1 i 40. id-din-šu-[n]u-ti-ma ana {d#}er₃-ra qar-rad DINGIR-MEŠ lil-li-ku i-da-a-šu

#tr.en: “When the noise of the peoples in settlements becomes unbearable to you,
41. %n kī ša nišī (|) dadmē | hubūršina || elīka | imtarṣu
#note: @bib{RN707@168-170} states that the “noise” here, as in @i{Atraḫasīs}, refers not to a rebellion of the humanity against the gods, as previously assumed, but simply to the uproar created by overpopulation.
NinNA1b i 8'. ki#-i# ša₂# UN-MEŠ da#-ad₂-me hu-bur-ši-na [U]GU*-ka im-tar-ṣu*
#note: Collation of Lambert @i{apud} @bib{RN31@Fig. 14}.
AššNA2 i 39'. [x x x UN]-MEŠ da-ad₂-me hu-bur-ši-na UGU#-ka# im-tar-ṣu
HuzNA1 i 41. ki-i ša UN-ME[Š d]a-ad₂#-me hu-bur-ši-na UGU-ka im-tar-ṣu

#tr.en: “And your temper drives you to decimate them,
42. %n ublam-ma | libbaka || ana šakān (|) kamāri
#note: As noted by @bib{RN31@156-157}, the literal meaning of the expression @i{kamāra šakānu}, very common in the Epic, could be “to lay a trap.” For more instances of the phrase, see @bib{RN2961@224}.
NinNA1b i 9'. ub-lam-ma lib₃-ba-ka a-na ša₂-kan [k]a-mar-ri
AššNA2 i 40'. [x x x] lib₃-ba-ka & a-na ša₂-kan ka-ma-ri
HuzNA1 i 42. ub-lam-ma [l]ib₃-ba-ka a-na ša₂-kan ka-ma-ri

#tr.en: “To ravage the black-headed and the wild beasts to destroy,
43. %n ṣalmāt (|) qaqqadi | ana šumutti || šumqut(u) (|) būl (|) šakkan
#note: The line uses a particularly elaborated chiasmus, as noted by @bib{temp_id_8182441432333507@289-290}.
NinNA1b i 10'. ṣal-mat SAG.DU a-na šu-mut-ti šum-q[u]-ut bu-ul {d}GIR₃
AššNA2 i 41'. [x x SAG.D]U ana šu-mut-ti šum-qu-tu bu-ul {d}GIR₃
HuzNA1 i 43. ṣal-mat SAG.DU a#-[n]a šu-mut-ti šum-qu-tu₄ bu-li₃ {d}GIR₃

#tr.en: “Let these be your wrathful weapons, that they march at your flank!”.
44. %n lū kakkūka | ezzūtu | šunū-ma || lillikū | idāka
NinNA1b i 11'. [l]u-u {giš}TUKUL#-MEŠ-ka ez-zu#-ti šu#-nu-ma [li]l-li#-ku# i-da#-ka
AššNA2 i 42'. [x x {giš}TUKUL-MEŠ-k]a ez-zu-ti šu-nu-ma lil-li-ku i-da#-a*-ka
#note: Collation of the line in Lambert’s folio 18397.
HuzNA1 i 44. lu-u₂ {giš}TUKUL-MEŠ-k[a e]z-zu-ti šu-nu-ma lil-li-ku!(LU) i-da-a-ka

#tr.en: They are furious, their weapons are raised,
45. %n šunu | ezzū-ma || tebû | kakkūšun
#note: On the expression @i{tebû kakkūšun}, “their weapons are raised,” see @bib{RN117@785}.
// cf. L I.4 SB "I" 63
// cf. L I.4 SB "I" 80
NinNA1b i 12'. šu#-nu ez-zu-ma# te*#-bu-u {giš}TUKUL-MEŠ-šu₂-un
#note: Collation of Lambert @i{apud} @bib{RN31@Fig. 14}.
AššNA2 i 43'. [x x ez-zu]-ma & te-bu-u₂ kak-°ka\ki°-šu₂-un
HuzNA1 i 45. šu-nu ez-zu-m[a] ti-bu-u₂ kak-ku-šu₂-un

#tr.en: They turn to Erra: “Rise! Stand up!
46. %n ītammû | ana erra || tibe | iziz-ma
NinNA1b i 13'. i#-ta#-mu-u a-na {d}er₃-ra te-be₂# i-ziz-ma
AššNA2 i 44'. [x x x x x x] {d*#}er₃*#-ra*# te-be₂ i-zi-iz-ma
HuzNA1 i 46. i-ta-mu-u₂ a-[n]a {d}er₃-ra ti-be₂ i-zi-iz-ma

#tr.en: “Why, like a worn-out old man, do you reside in a city,
47. %n minsu | kī šībi | muqqi || tušib | ina āli
// cf. L III.10 13
NinNA1b i 14'. min₃#-su# ki#-i# ši-i#-bi muq*-qi₂ tu*#-šib ina a-li*#
#note: Collation of Lambert @i{apud} @bib{RN31@Fig. 14}.
AššNA2 i 45'. [x x x x x x x x x tu]-ši-ib ina* URU*#
#note: As noted by @bib{RN31@162}, the uncorrected version of the copy, @akk{ina a-LAM}, would represent the only syllabic writing of @i{ālu}, “city,” in the entire Epic (but cf. MS NinNA1b in this line). Collation of the line follows Lambert’s folio 18397.
HuzNA1 i 47. min₃-su ki-i ši-i#-bi muq-qi₂ & tu-šib ina URU

#tr.en: “Like a little child do you reside in a house?
48. %n kī šerri | laʾî || tušib | ina bīti
NinNA1b i 15'. ki#-i# šer₃-ri la-ʾ-u₂*# & tu*#-šib ina E₂
#note: For the collation @akk{tu*#-šib}, see Lambert @i{apud} @bib{RN31@Fig. 14}.
