AššNASch5 r 4. ki-i l[a x x x x x x x x x x]
$ end of excerpt

#tr.en: “As if we did not know how to fight, should we tremble and fear?
50. %n kī ša tāhāza | lā nīdû || niplaha | nirūda
#note: The use of preterites in this line (@i{niplaḫa}, @i{nirūda}), as opposed to the present in the previous line (@i{nikkala}) has not been explained (@bib{temp_id_07390035038145881@202} states that it is “schwer zu erklären”; @bib{RN31@163} simply refers to him). The most likely explanation is that @i{niplaḫa} and @i{nirūda} represent cohortatives without @i{i} (@bib{RN27201@§81g}) used as a rhetorical question (@bib{RN27201@§153g}). A cohortative without @i{i} also occurs in @i{Erra and Išum} V 18 (q.v.).
NinNA1b i 17'. ki#-i# ša₂ ta-ha-za la# ni-du-u ni-ip-la-h[a*] ni-ru*#-da*#
#note: Collation of Lambert @i{apud} @bib{RN31@Fig. 14}.
AššNA2 i 48'. [x x x x x x x x x x ni-i]p-la-ha n[i]-ru#-[da]
HuzNA1 i 50. ki-i ša₂ ta-ha-zi la# ni-du-u₂ & ni-ip-la-ha ni-ru-da

#tr.en: “Going to the (battle) field is becoming for manhood, like a festival!
51. %n alāk (|) ṣēri | ša eṭlūti | kī ša isinnum-ma
#note: @bib{NABU1990-56@56} interprets @akk{ki-i ša₂} as @i{kīša}, “certainly”: “Das Zufeldeziehen der Mannen ist doch gewiss ein Fest.” This understanding, however, should be ruled out, since a manuscript of one of the passages discussed by von Soden (III 140-141) writes @akk{ki-ma ša₂} (see @i{ad loc}.). Compare Lambert’s understanding, “Going to the manly battle field is like a festival” (@bib{RN706@400}).
NinNA1b i 18'. a-lak EDIN ša₂ eṭ-lu-ti & ki-i# ša₂# i#-[s]in-nu-im-ma
AššNA2 i 49'. [x x x x x x x x x x] i#-si[n-nu-um-ma]
$ rest of column broken
HuzNA1 i 51. a-lak EDIN ša₂ eṭ-lu-ti# ki-i ša₂ i-sin-nu-um-ma

#tr.en: “The city dweller, be he a prince, bread does not satiate him,
52. %n āšib (|) āli | lū rubû || ul išebbi | akla
#note: According to @bib{RN31@163-164}, “Il senso del verso è che il combattere procura il cibo (attraverso il bottino).”
NinNA1b i 19'. a#-šib URU lu NUN* ul*# i!?-šeb-b[i] ak#-la
#note: Collation @akk{NUN} of Lambert @i{apud} @bib{RN31@Fig. 14}.
HuzNA1 i 52. a-šib URU <lu> NUN-u₂ ul i-šeb-bi ak-la

#tr.en: “Criticized by his own people, despised,
53. %n šumsuk | ina pī (|) nišīšū-ma || qalil | qaqqassu
// cf. L II.3 21
NinNA1b i 20'. šum*-suk ina pi-i U[N-MEŠ-šu₂-ma x x qa]q-qad-su
#note: Collation of Lambert @i{apud} @bib{RN31@Fig. 14}.
HuzNA1 i 53. šum-suk ina KA UN-MEŠ-šu₂-ma# & qa-lil SAG.DU-su

#tr.en: “He will have to beg to the humblest soldier.
54. %n ana ālik (|) ṣēri | akî || itarraṣ | qāssu
#note: @i{akî} here and in l. 56 has been universally interpreted as an interrogative adverb @i{akī}, which makes the understanding of these lines difficult. As noted in the comment to III 54, it is best to interpret it as the adjective @i{akû}, “humble.” 
// cf. L I.4 SB "III" 61
NinNA1b i 21'. a-na a-lik EDIN a-ki-i!?# [x x x x Š]U-su
HuzNA1 i 54. a-na a-lik EDIN a-ki-i i-tar-ra-aṣ qa-as-su

#tr.en: “The city dweller, however mighty his strength,
55. %n ša āšib (|) āli || lū puggulat | kubukkuš
NinNA1b i 22'. ša₂ a-šib URU lu p[u!?-ug-gu-lat ku-bu-uk]-kuš
HuzNA1 i 55. ša₂ a-šib URU lu pu-ug-gu#-lat# & <<lu>> ku-bu-uk-ku-[uš]
#note: Collation in @bib{RN728@92} (“correctly copied”).

#tr.en: “In what does it advantage the humblest soldier?
56. %n ana ālik (|) ṣēri | akî || idannin | mīna
NinNA1b i 23'. a-na a-lik EDIN a-ki-i*# [x x x mi]-i!?#-na#
#note: Collation of Lambert @i{apud} @bib{RN31@Fig. 14}.
HuzNA1 i 56. a-na a-lik EDIN a-ki-i i-dan#-nin m[i]-i#-n[u]

#tr.en: “The abundant bread of the city cannot compare with the cake baked in embers!
57. %n akal (|) āli | lullû || ul ubbala | kamān (|) tumri
#note: Compare @bib{RN706@400b}: “The sense of @akk{ub-ba-la} is probably ‘fetch (a price)’, and thus «X is not equal in value to Y».” See @bib{NABU2006-66@66} for some ethnographic parallels to the “bread baked in ashes.”
NinNA1b i 24'. a-kal URU lul-lu-u# [x x x x x x tum₃]-ri
HuzNA1 i 57. a-kal URU lul-lu-u₂ ul ub#-ba-la ka-man# tum₃#-[ri]

#tr.en: “The fine, honeyed beer cannot compare with the water from a waterskin!
58. %n šikar (|) našpi || duššupi || ul ubbala | mê (|) nādi
#note: @bib{RN3078@105} identifies @i{šikar našpi} with Sumerian @sux{kaš sig}, “golden beer.”
NinNA1b i 25'. ši-kar# na-aš₂-pi [x x x x x x x x x x na]-a#-di#
HuzNA1 i 58. ši-kar na-aš₂-pi du-uš-šu-pi ul# ub-ba-lu A-[M]EŠ n[a]-a-[di]

#tr.en: “The palace on the citadel cannot compare with the shepherd’s hut!
59. %n ēkal (|) tamlî | ul ubbala | maṣallu | ša r[ēʾ]î
#note: The reading of the last word follows @bib{temp_id_07390035038145881@203} (see also @bib{RN31@165}), as opposed to @akk{ma-ṣal-la tu-ša₂-[ri]} (@bib{RN706@400b}, a reading now rendered impossible by MS NinNA3).
NinNA1b i 26'. E₂*#.GAL*# [x x x x x x x x x x re-ʾ]-i!?#
#note: Collation of Lambert @i{apud} @bib{RN31@Fig. 14}.
NinNA3 ii 1. [x x x x x x x x x m]a-ṣal-lu ša₂ SI[PA]
#note: According to @bib{RN419@76b}, the last sign “may be @akk{S[IPA]}, but cannot be @akk{{l[u₂}SIPA]}.”
HuzNA1 i 59. E₂.GAL tam-li-i ul ub-ba-la ma#-ṣal-la-tu ša₂# [x (x)]

#tr.en: “Warrior Erra, go out into the (battle) field, rattle your weapons!
60. %n qurādu | erra | ṣī-ma | ana ṣēri | turuk | kakkīka
NinNA1b i 27'. [qu-r]a!?-d[u!? x x x x x x x x x x {giš}TUKUL-(MEŠ)-k]a
$ end of side
NinNA3 ii 2. [x x x x x x x x x x EDI]N tu-ruk kak-ki-ka
HuzNA1 i 60. qu-ra-du {d}er₃-ra ṣi-i-ma ana EDIN# tu-ruk [{giš}]TUKUL-MEŠ-[k]a

#tr.en: “Make your noise loud, so that those above and below tremble!
61. %n rigimka | dunnin-ma || lištarʾibū | eliš (|) u šapliš
NinNA3 ii 3. [x x x x x x x x x x] e#-liš u šap-liš
