HuzNA1 ii 27. min₃-su# še-ma-ta-ma & qa-liš tu-u[š-ša₂-b]u

#tr.en: “Open the path, I shall take to the road!
96. %n ṭūda | pitē-ma || luṣbat | harrā[n]a
// L I.5 SB "II" 128
// L I.5 SB "III" 130
NinNA1b ii 5'. ṭu*-di p[i-te-ma lu-u]ṣ-ba-ta ha[r-ra-na]
#note: Collation of Lambert @i{apud} @bib{RN31@Fig. 14}. Second half of the line preserved in K.19050.
AššNA2 ii 34'. ṭu-da pi-i-ti-ma lu#-u[ṣ-b]a-ta har-ra-[nu]
HuzNA1 ii 28. ṭu-da# pi-te*-ma & lu-uṣ-bat har-r[a-n]i
#note: Collation in @bib{RN2069@23}.

#tr.en: “Let the Seven, the peerless warriors, make war!
97. %n sebettu | qarrād (|) lā šanān || lupp[išū] | t[āhāz]a
#note: The parallel in III 133 allows now the correct restoration of the line. @bib{RN31@176} reconstructed @akk{lu-up#-p[it?]}.
// L I.5 SB "III" 131
NinNA1b ii 6'a. {d}IMIN-BI q[ar*-rad x x x x x x x x (x) x]
#note: Collation of Lambert @i{apud} @bib{RN31@Fig. 14}.
AššNA2 ii 35'a. {d}IMIN-BI qar-rad la ša₂#-n[a*-an x x x x (x) x]
#note: Collation of the line in Lambert’s folio 18397. At the end, space does not seem to allow the restoration @i{luppišū tāḫāza}; perhaps the line in this manuscript (and also in NinNA1b) read simply: @i{qarrād lā šanān šūlika idāya},
$ line continues
HuzNA1 ii 29. {d}IMIN-BI q[a]r-rad la ša₂-na-an lu-up#-p[iš?] t[a-ha-z]a
#note: Collation in @bib{RN728@92} (“97 end Final trace probably head of a vertical”).

#tr.en: “Make my fierce weapons march to my flank!
98. %n kakkī[y]a | ezzūti || šūlika | idāya
// L I.5 SB "III" 132
NinNA1b ii 6'b. [x x x x ez-zu-t]u šu-li-ka i?#-[da-a-a]
#note: Second half of the line preserved in K.19050.
AššNA2 ii 35'b. [x x x ez-zu-t]u!? šu-li-k[a!?] i-da-a-a
HuzNA1 ii 30. {giš}TUKUL-MEŠ-[i]a ez-zu-tu šu-li-ku# i#-[da-a-a]

#tr.en: “And you, my champion, come before me!”.
99. %n u attā | ālik (|) mahrīya || alik | pā[nī]ya
#note: Formerly @i{arkīya} was reconstructed at the end, apparently confirmed by collation of MS AššNA2 (so @bib{RN31@177 fn. 116}). However, as already suggested by Borger @i{apud} @bib{RN31@177 fn. 116}, the obvious command to a “champion” (@i{ālik maḫrīya}) would be for him to “march ahead” (@i{alik pānīya}), a supposition now confirmed by the identical line in III 133.
// L I.5 SB "III" 133
NinNA1b ii 7'. u at-ta# a*#-[lik x x x] a-lik# [x x x]
#note: Collation of Lambert @i{apud} @bib{RN31@Fig. 14}. Second half of the line preserved in K.19050.
AššNA2 ii 36'. u₃ at#-ta a-lik ma[h-ri-i]a a-lik pa?#-[ni]-ia
#note: Collation of the line in Lambert’s folio 18397 (only one horizontal after @akk{a-lik}). The collation of L. Jakob-Rost @i{apud} @bib{RN31@177 fn. 116} suggested a reading @akk{EGIR} (the KAR copy admits a reading @akk{ar₂#-[ki]-ia#})..
HuzNA1 ii 31. u₃ at-ta# a-lik mah-ri-ia [a-li]k pa#-[ni-ia]

#tr.en: [When] Išum [heard] these words,
100. %n īšum | annīta | [ina šemêšu]
NinNA1b ii 8'. {d}i-šu[m x x x x x x]
#note: The preserved surface of K.19050 seems to be blank in this line, which probably indicates that the line was written in a spaced-out manner.
HuzNA1 ii 32. {d#}i#-š[u]m an-ni-ta [x x x x x]

100. %n [iš]mē-ma | īš[um | ann]â | qabâ | [(ša) err]a
// L I.5 SB "III" 134
AššNA2 ii 37'. [iš]-me-e-ma# {d}i-š[um an-na]-a qa-ba#-a# [(ša₂) {d}er₃-r]a!?

#tr.en: Moved with compassion he said, [“alas!”]
101. %n rēma | irt[ašī-(ma) || iqt]abi | [ahūlap]
// L I.5 SB "III" 135
AššNA2 ii 38'. {(10)} re-e-mu ir#-t[a-ši iq-t]a-bi# [x x x]
#note: Collation of the line in Lambert’s folio 18397: “@i{re} now gone; traces doubtful.”

101. %n īpuš-ma | pâšu | izakkar | [ana qurā]di | e[rra]
NinNA1b ii 9'. <i>-pu-uš!?# (x) [x x x (x x)] i?#-[x x x x x x x x]
#note: See the collation of Lambert @i{apud} @bib{RN31@Fig. 14}. The sign @akk{i?#-[...]} is preserved in K.19050.
HuzNA1 ii 33. i#-[pu-uš]-ma?# pa-a-še i-zak-kar [x qu-ra]-du {d}e[r₃-ra]
#note: As noted by @bib{RN31@177}, MS HuzNA1 uses @i{-še} for the suffix @i{-šu} also in I 104, 126, and 180.

#tr.en: “Warrior Erra, why have you devised insidious plots against the gods?
102. %n (qurādu | erra) | minsu | ana il[ī || lemu]tta | takp[ud]
#note: For parallels to the expression “to plot evil” against the gods in the Epic, see @bib{RN31@177-178}. According to him, the planned “evil” is the destruction that Erra prepares.
NinNA1b ii 10'. qu#-ra#-du# [x x x x x x x x x x x]
AššNA2 ii 39'. min₃-su a-na DINGIR-[MEŠ le-mu]-ut!?-tu₂# tak#-[pu-ud]
HuzNA1 ii 34. qu!?#-r[a!?-du] {d!?#}er₃-ra min₃-su a-[na x x HU]L-ti₃ tak-p[u-ud]
#note: Cagni’s reading of MS HuzNA1 @akk{be-lu₄}, is difficult, since Erra never receives the epithet @i{bēlu} elsewhere in the Epic (@bib{RN31@177}). A reading @akk{qu#-r[a-du]} seems easier to reconcile with the traces as copied.

#tr.en: “You have plotted to ravage the earth and destroy [its inhabitants]; will you not desist?”
103. %n ana sapān | mātāti | hulluq (|) [nišīšin | lemu]tta | takpud-ma | lā t[atūr | ana a]rkīka
#note: Compare the close paralllel in an Esarhaddon inscription mentioned by @bib{RN31@178}: @akk{{d}EN.LIL₂.LA₅ | DINGIR#-MEŠ {d}AMAR.UTU a-na sa-pan | KUR# hul-lu-qu UN-MEŠ-ša₂ | ik-ta-pu-ud HUL-ti₃}, “The Enlil of [the go]ds, the god Marduk, became angry and plotted evilly to level the land (and) to destroy its people” (@bib{RN393@Esarhaddon 104} i 34-37).
// L I.5 SB "II" 27
// L I.5 SB "II" 67
// L I.5 SB "III" 142
// L I.5 SB "V" 40
NinNA1b ii 11'. ana# sa*#-pan*# KUR*#.KUR!?# h[ul!?-lu-uq x x x x x x x x x x x x x x x]
#note: Collation of Lambert @i{apud} @bib{RN31@Fig. 14}.
AššNA2 ii 40'. ana sa*#-pan*# KUR.KUR hul#-lu-u[q x x x HU]L!?-tu₂ tak-pu#-ud#-[ma x x x x ar₂]-k[i!?-k]a!?
#note: Collation of the line in Lambert’s folio 18397, who adds: “last @i{ud} uncertain.”
HuzNA1 ii 35-36. a-na sa-pan# [KUR.KU]R hul-lu-uq! [x x (x) HUL]-ti₃ tak-pu-ud-ma | ($___$) la# t[a-tur x a]r-ki-ka

#tr.en: Erra prepared to speak,
104. %n erra | pâšu || īpuš-[ma] | iqabbi
// L I.5 SB "III" 143
NinNA1b ii 12'. {d}er₃-ra [x x x x x x x x x]
AššNA2 ii 41'a. {d}er₃-ra KA-šu₂ DU₃-[ma DUG₄].GA
$ line continues
HuzNA1 ii 37. {d}er₃-ra [pa-a-š]e i-[pu-uš-ma] i-qab-bi

#tr.en: Addressing Išum, his champion, in these words:
105. %n ana īšum | ā[li]k (|) mahrīšu || [amāta] | izakkar
// L I.5 SB "III" 144
NinNA1b ii 13'. ana# {d#}i#-šum# a*#-[lik x x x x x x x x x]
AššNA2 ii 41'b. ana {d}i-š[um a-li]k mah-r[i-šu₂ x x x x]
$ line continues
HuzNA1 ii 38. a-na {d}i#-[šu]m a#-[lik m]ah-ri#-šu₂# [x x (x)] i-zak-kar

#tr.en: “Išum, pay attention, listen to my words!
106. %n īšum | qūlam-ma || šime | qabâya
// L I.5 SB "III" 180
// L I.5 SB "V" 17
NinNA1b ii 14'. {d#}i#-šum# [x x x x x x x x]
AššNA2 ii 42'. {d}i-šum q[u*]-lam-ma še-mi qa-ba-a-a
#note: Collation of the line in Lambert’s folio 18397.
HuzNA1 ii 39. {d}i-š[u]m qu-[l]a-ma ši-[mi] qa-ba-a-a

#tr.en: “Concerning the peoples in settlements, whose pardon you requested,
107. %n aššu nišī (|) dadmē || ša taqbû | gamālšin
// L I.5 SB "III" 181
NinNA1b ii 15'. aš₂*#-šu₂*# UN#-ME[Š x x x x x x x x x x]
#note: Collation of Lambert @i{apud} @bib{RN31@Fig. 14}.
AššNA2 ii 43'. aš₂-šu₂# UN#-M[EŠ da-a]d₂-me ša₂ taq-bu-u ga-mal₂-šin*#
#note: Collation of the line in Lambert’s folio 18397.
HuzNA1 ii 40. aš₂-šu₂ n[i!?-š]i da-ad₂-[m]e ša₂ taq-bu-u [ga-m]a-al-šin

#tr.en: “O champion of the gods, wise Išum, whose counsel is sweet!
108. %n ālik (|) mahri (|) ilī | enqu | īšum | ša milikšu | damqu
#note: As noted by @bib{RN1811@43}, @bib{RN55aa@148}, and @bib{RN31@178}, the passage is ironic. Gössmann speaks of “offensichtlich beißende Ironie.”
// L I.5 SB "III" 182
NinNA1b ii 16'. a*#-lik*# mah#-ri# D[INGIR-MEŠ x x x x x x x x x x x]
#note: Collation of Lambert @i{apud} @bib{RN31@Fig. 14}.
AššNA2 ii 44'. a#-l[ik!? x x] DINGIR-MEŠ en-qu {d}i-šum ša₂# mi₃*#-lik#-šu₂ dam-qu#
#note: Collation of the line in Lambert’s folio 18397.
HuzNA1 ii 41. a-li[k ma]h-ri DINGIR-MEŠ en#-q[u] {d#}i-šum ša₂ mi-li[k]-šu₂# dam-qu
$ single ruling

#tr.en: “In heaven I am a wild bull, on earth I am a lion,
109. %n ina šamê | rīmāku || ina erṣeti | labbāku
#note: @bib{RN1811@43} calls this passage “ein Musterbeispiel bab. Poesie.” See the thorough study of the lines in @bib{cohen2013fearful@1-28}.
// L I.5 SB "III" 183
// L III.7 54
NinNA1b ii 17'. ina AN*#-e*# r[i*-ma-ku x x x x x x]
#note: Collation of Lambert @i{apud} @bib{RN31@Fig. 14}.
AššNA2 ii 45'. i[na!? x x] ri-ma-ku & ina KI-ti₃ lab-ba#-ku
HuzNA1 ii 42. ina A[N]-e# ri-ma-k[u] & ina KI-ti₃ & [l]ab-ba-ka
#note: Collation in @bib{RN2069@23} (“109-127 The cracks should be wider”).

#tr.en: “In the land I am a king, among the gods a fury,
110. %n ina māti | šarrāku || ina ilī | ezzāku
// L I.5 SB "III" 184
NinNA1b ii 18'. ina KUR šar#-[ra-ku x x x x x x]
AššNA2 ii 46'. [x x] šar!(ŠIR₃)-ra-ku & ina DINGIR-MEŠ ez-za-ku#
HuzNA1 ii 43. [x K]UR šar-ra-k[u] & ina DINGIR-MEŠ [e]z-ze#-ka

#tr.en: “Among the Igigi I am a hero, among the Anunnaki a champion,
111. %n ina igīgī | qardāku || ina anunnakī | gašrāku
// L I.5 SB "III" 185
NinNA1b ii 19'. ina {d}i₂-gi₃-gi₃ qar*#-d[a*-ku x x x x x x x x x]
#note: Collation of Lambert @i{apud} @bib{RN31@Fig. 14}.
AššNA2 ii 47'. [x x x x x] qar-da-ku & ina {d}a-nun-<na>-ki gaš-ra-ku
HuzNA1 ii 44. [x] {d#}i₂-gi₃-gi₃ qar-da-k[u] & ina {d}a-nun-na-ki & gaš-rak

#tr.en: “Among the beasts I am a bowhunter, in the mountain the pit-trap,
112. %n ina būli | māhiṣāku || ina šadî | šubāku
#note: On the translation “archer” or “bowhunter” of @i{māḫiṣu}, and “pit-trap” of @i{šubāku}, see the commentary on III 186.
// L I.5 SB "III" 186
// cf. L I.5 SB "IV" 93
NinNA1b ii 20'. ina bu-li ma*#-hi*#-ṣ[a-ku x x x x x x]
#note: Collation of Lambert @i{apud} @bib{RN31@Fig. 14}.
AššNA2 ii 48'. [x x x] ma#-hi-ṣa-ku & ina KUR-i*# šu#-ba-ku
#note: Collation of the line in Lambert’s folio 18397.
HuzNA1 ii 45. [x b]u-li₃ ma-hi-ṣa-k[u] & ina KUR-i & šu-ba-ku#

#tr.en: “In the reedbed I am the fire, in the forest the axe,
113. %n ina api | gīrāk[u] || ina qīši | magšarāku
// L I.5 SB "III" 187
NinNA1b ii 21'. ina a-pi {d#}gi[ra₂-ku x x x x x x]
AššNA2 ii 49'. [x x x x x & x x x ma-ag-ša₂-ra]-ku!?#
$ rest of column broken
HuzNA1 ii 46. ina a#-[p]i {d}gira₂-k[u?] & ina qi₂-ši ma-ag*#-ša₂-rak
#note: Collation of @akk{ma-ag*#-ša₂-rak} in @bib{RN2069@23}. See also the collation in Lambert’s folio 18397.

#tr.en: “In campaign I am the standard,
114. %n ina alāk (|) harrāni | urinnāku
// L I.5 SB "III" 188
NinNA1b ii 22'. ina a-lak* h[ar-ra-ni x x x x x]
#note: Collation of @bib{RN706@401a} and @i{apud} @bib{RN31@Fig. 14}.
HuzNA1 ii 47. ina a-l[a]k har-ra-nu & u₂-ri-in-na-ku
#note: The reading @akk{a-lak!} stems from von Soden @i{apud} @bib{temp_id_07390035038145881@205}. @bib{RN1811@114} reads @akk{a-li[k]}. According to the copy, the third sign could also be read as @akk{l[i]k}. The parallel in tablet III seems to read @i{a-lik}, which should probably be interpreted as a @i{parīs} infinitive (@bib{RN27201@§87k}).

#tr.en: “As the wind I blow, as Adad I thunder;
115. %n kī šāri | azâq || kī addi | ur[t]aṣṣan
// L I.5 SB "III" 189
NinNA1b ii 23'. ki-i ša₂-a*#-r[i* x x x x x x x x x x x]
#note: Collation of Lambert @i{apud} @bib{RN31@Fig. 14}.
HuzNA1 ii 48. ki-i IM# a-za-qu ki-i {d}IŠKUR ur#-[t]a-ṣa-an

#tr.en: “Like the sun god I oversee the whole orb.
116. %n kī [ša]mši | abarri || [k]ippata | [k]alāma
// L I.5 SB "III" 190
NinNA1b ii 24'. ki*#-i*# [x x x x x x x x x x x x]
#note: Collation of Lambert @i{apud} @bib{RN31@Fig. 14}.
$ end of column
HuzNA1 ii 49. ki-i {d#}[U]TU-ši a-bar#-ri# [k]ip-pa-ta [k]a-la-ma

#tr.en: “When I go forth into the field I am a wild goat;
117. %n ana ṣ[ē]ri | uṣṣī-ma | bi[b]bāku
// L I.5 SB "III" 191
HuzNA1 ii 50. a-na E[DI]N uṣ#-ṣi#-ma bi-i[b]-ba-ku

#tr.en: “When I enter the steppe, as Nergal do I take residence.
118. %n ana n[a]mî | errub-ma | nergal | ram[âk]u | šubta
#note: Previous attempts at restoring this line (e.g. @bib{RN31@180 fn. 125}, @bib{cagni1977poem@31 n. 30}, @bib{NABU2013-10@10}, @bib{cohen2013fearful@4-5}) can now be proven wrong thanks to the parallel in tablet III.
// L I.5 SB "III" 192
HuzNA1 ii 51. a-na n[a]-me-e er-ru-ub-ma {d#}U#.GUR# ra-m[a-k]u šub-ta

#tr.en: “The gods all fear my name.
119. %n ilū | napharšunu || nib[ī]tī | šahtū
#note: Previous attempts at restoring this line (e.g. @bib{RN31@180}) should now be abandoned in view of the parallel in tablet III. It is interpreted that the writing @i{-ta} in @akk{ni-b[i!?]-ta#} reflects an implicit first-person suffix @i{-i}, since the parallel in III 193 does have the suffix.
// L I.5 SB "III" 193
HuzNA1 ii 52. DINGIR-MEŠ# nap-har#-šu₂-nu ni-b[i!?]-ta# šah-tu

#tr.en: “And yet, the black-headed people despise me.
120. %n u nišī | ṣalmā[t (|) q]aqqadi || leq[û] | šēṭūtī
#note: @bib{RN31@181} notes that this is the only instance in which @i{šēṭūtu} is used without a personal suffix, and speculates that the suffix may have been omitted “per indicare un atteggiamento più generale.” Note, however, that the suffix is written in the parallel line III 197, and that MS HuzNA1 also omits the first-person possessive suffix of a word in the previous line.
// L I.5 SB "III" 194
// cf. L I.5 SB "III" 212
// cf. L I.5 SB "IV" 113
HuzNA1 ii 53. u₃# UN-MEŠ ṣal-ma[t S]AG.DU le-q[u-u₂] ši-ṭu-tu₄

#tr.en: “I — for they have not feared my name
121. %n anāku | aššu lā išhuṭū-(ma) | zikrī
// L I.5 SB "III" 195
HuzNA1 ii 54. a-na-ku aš₂-šu₂ la aš₂-hu-ṭu-ma zik-ri
#note: The writing /@i{aš}/ of MS HuzNA1 can be explained as a sandhi writing (@i{lā}~@i{ašḫuṭū-ma}), or else as another case of the preference for the /@i{a}/ vowel in Sultantepe manuscripts, on which see @bib{RN404@125–126}, @bib{RN117@370}, and @bib{RN1013@11}.
AššNASch2 r 7a. a-na-ku aš₂-šu₂ la iš-hu-tu₂ zik-ri :.
$ beginning of excerpt
$ line continues

#tr.en: “And have neglected the orders of prince Marduk, I shall do as he pleases.
122. %n u ša rubê | marūtuk | amāssu | iddû-ma | eppuš(u) | kī libbuš
#note: The understanding of @akk{ep-pu-šu} // @akk{[e]p-pu-uš} in the first person follows a suggestion by E. Tadmor.
// L I.5 SB "III" 196
HuzNA1 ii 55. u₃# ša₂ NUN {d}AMAR.UTU a-mat-su id-du-[ma e]p-pu-uš ki-i lib-bu-uš
AššNASch2 r 7b. u₃ ša₂ NUN {d}AMAR.UTU a-mat-su id-du-ma ep-pu-šu ki-i lib-bu-uš
#note: Compare @bib{RN31@181}: “Nella Var. @akk{ip-pu-šu} si ha @i{-u} sovrabbondante, possibilmente con funzione sintattica (espressione di una conseguenza: cfr. Comm. a I, 20: Excursus).”

#tr.en: “I shall make prince Marduk angry, I shall raise him from his throne and devastate mankind.”
123. %n rubâ | marūtuk | ušaggag-ma | ina šubtīšu | adekkē-ma | nišī | asappan
#note: Compare @bib{RN31@181}: “la collera di Marduk ha una precisa giustificazione nella colpa degli uomini (vv. 120-122); il suo allontanamento, causato dalla stessa collera, ha come conseguenza le terribili distruzioni, qui sintetizzate da Erra con il semplice ‘gli uomini abbatterò’, ma che hanno una ben più vasta portata, come sappiamo dal resoconto di una sua manifestazione di collera (I, 132-137) e dalla descrizione delle malvagità di Erra (Tavv. II-IV).”
HuzNA1 ii 56. NUN {d}AMAR.UTU u₂-šag-gag-ma ina šub-t[i-šu₂ a]-de-ke-ma UN-MEŠ a-sa-pan
AššNASch2 r 8. NUN-a {d}AMAR.UTU u₂-šag-gag-ma ina šub-ti#-šu₂ a-de-ke-ma UN#-MEŠ a-sa-ap-pan

#tr.en: The warrior Erra set off to Šuʾanna, the city of the king of the gods,
124. %n qurādu | erra | ana šuʾanna | āl (|) šar (|) ilī | ištakan | pānīšu
#note: The epithet “city of the king of the gods” of Šuʾanna (i.e., Babylon) is also known from @i{Tintir} I 13 (see @bib{RN124@247}.
HuzNA1 ii 57. qu-ra-du {d}er₃-ra ana šu-an-n[a U]RU LUGAL DINGIR-MEŠ iš-ta-kan pa-ni-šu₂
AššNASch2 r 9. qu-ra-du {d}er₃-ra a-na šu-an-na URU LUGAL DINGIR.DINGIR# iš-ta-kan pa-ni-šu

#tr.en: He entered the Esagil, the palace of heaven and earth, and presented himself before him.
125. %n ana ēsagil | ēkal (|) šamê (|) (u) erṣeti | īrum-ma | ittaziz | pānuššu
HuzNA1 ii 58. ana e₂-sag-il₂ E₂.GAL AN-e u K[I-ti₃] i#-ru-um-ma it-ta-ziz pa-nu-uš-šu₂
AššNASch2 r 10. a-na e₂#-sag-il₂ E₂#.GAL AN-e KI-ti₃ i-ru-um#-ma it-ta-ziz pa-nu-uš-šu

#tr.en: He prepared to speak, addressing the king of the gods:
126. %n īpuš-ma | pâšu || ana šar (|) ilī | ītammi
HuzNA1 ii 59. i-pu-uš-ma pa-a-še <ana> LU[GAL DI]NGIR-MEŠ i#-ta-mi#
AššNA2 iii 1'. [x x x x x x x x x x x x i-ta]-ma
AššNASch2 r 11. e-pu-uš-ma pa-a-šu a-na LUGAL DINGIR.DINGIR i-ta-ma

#tr.en: “The image, the ornament of your lordship, which, like the stars of heaven, was full of splendor, why is it covered with filth?
127. %n minsu | šukuttu | simat (|) bēlūtīka | ša kīma kakkab(ī) (|) šamāmī | lulâ | malât | leqât | urūša
#note: The exact translation of @i{šukuttu} is debated: some authors prefer a more general translation “jewel” (@bib{RN706@299}) or “prezioso apparato” (@bib{RN31@183}), others understand that it refers to Marduk’s statue (so e.g. @bib{cassin1968splendeur@49 fn. 86}, followed by @bib{RN984@192}). The last word was interpreted as @i{urūšu}/@i{urrušu}, related to @i{arāšu}, “to be(come) dirty” @bib{temp_id_07390035038145881@205} and as @i{aršu}, “dirty,” by @bib{RN31@183}. @bib{RN2721@U/W 248b} parses it as @i{urrušu}, “filthy person or thing.” @bib{RN31@188} compares the passage with the following lines in an inscription of Esarhaddon (@bib{RN393@Esarhaddon 104 iv 9-17}): “I repaired the woeful desecrated state of the gods and goddess who lived in it, who had been displaced by floods and storm, and whose appearances had become dim; I made their dimmed appearance bright, cleaned their dirty garments, (and) had them permanently installed on their daises.” (@akk{DINGIR-MEŠ u {d}iš-tar a-ši-bu-ut | qer-bi-šu ša₂ A-MEŠ bu-tuq-tu | u₃ ra-a-du u₂-bi-lu-šu₂-nu-ti-ma | i-ki-lu ši-ki-in-šu-un | šal-pu-ut-ta-šu₂-nu lu-mu-un-tu₂ | ud-diš zi-me-šu₂-nu uk-ku-lu-tu | u₂-ša₂-an-biṭ ṣu-bat-su-nu | ar-šu ub-bi-ib ina BARA₂-ME-šu₂-nu | da-riš u₂-šar-me-šu₂-nu-ti}).
HuzNA1 ii 60-61. min₃-su šu-kut-ti si-mat be-lu-ti-ka# [x x] MUL-MEŠ ša₂#-ma#-[me] lu#-la-a ma-la-at# | [l]e-qa-a!?#-[t]i!? u₂-ru-ši
$ end of column
AššNA2 iii 2'. [x x x x x x x x x x x x x x x x x x x x x x x x x x x u₂]-ru#-u-ša₂*#
#note: Collation of the line in Lambert’s folio 18398.
AššNASch2 r 12. min₃-su šu-kut-ta si-mat be-lu-ti-ka ša₂ GIM kak#-kab ša₂-ma-me lu-la#-a ma-la#-at₂# le-qa-ta ur#-šiš!?#
#note: @akk{ma-la#-at₂#} could also be read as @akk{ma-la#-ta#}

#tr.en: “The diadem of your lordship, which used to make the Eḫalanki shine like the Etemenanki, why is it dimmed?
128. %n agê (|) bēlūtīka | (ša) kīma ētemenanki | ušanbiṭu | ēhalanki | pānūšu | katmū
#note: Etemenanki is the ziggurat of Marduk in Babylon; Eḫalanki is the seat of Zarpanitu in her cella in the Esagil (@bib{RN1914@149 no. 1088 and 98 no. 448, respectively}). On the comparison, see @bib{RN600@84-85}. Compare the translation in @bib{RN164@887}: “which made the inner sanctum shine like the outside tower.”
HuzNA1 iii 1-2. a-ge-e# be₂-lu-ti-ka# GIM# e₂-te-me-en-an-ki u₂-nam-ma-ri# | ($___$) e₂-hal-an-k[i] pa-nu-šu kat₃#-m[u]
AššNA2 iii 3'-4'. [x x x x x x x x x x x x x x] u₂#-ša₂-an-bi-ṭu | ($___$) [x x x x x x x ka]t₃!?-mu
AššNASch2 r 13. a-ge-e be-lu-ti-ka ša!?# ki-ma °DIŠ\° e₂-te-me-na#-ak u₂-ša₂-an-ba-ṭu e₂-hal#-an#-ki pa-nu-šu kat₃-mu
#note: Compare @bib{RN31@183 fn. 134}: “Gössmann, ad loc., segue l’esempI. D, una tavoletta scolastica che ha una scrittura erronea nel nome del primo tempio e un @i{ana} erroneo sia qui sia nel v. prec.: «Die Krone deiner Herrschaft: lässt man sie gen Etemenak leuchten, so ist das Antlitz von é.ḫal.an.ki bedeckt».”

