#tr.en: “Once, in my anger, I arose from my throne, causing a flood;
132. %n ultu (|) ullu | āgugū-ma | ina šubtīya | atbû-ma | aškuna | abūba
#note: It is uncertain whether the word @i{abūbu} refers to the Flood or to any catastrophe in general. The latter interpretation seems more likely since, as noted by @bib{RN31@184-186}, Enlil is in Mesopotamian mythology the god responsible for sending the flood, and this seems to be the case also in the Epic: in IV 50, it is stated that “Lord of the Lands” (i.e., Enlil) spared Sippar from the Flood, which probably implies that it was also Enlil who sent it. See also @bib{RN801@251-253, 274-278}, who remarks that in the Epic the cause of the Flood is not the overpopulation of the earth. In any case, the subordinative in @i{a-gu-gu-ma} and @i{at-bu-ma} mean that @i{ultu ullu} cannot be taken as an adverbial expression (pace @bib{RN1826@251-252}, “depuis longtemps,” “autrefois”), but rather a conjunction, with @bib{RN27201@§174g*}.
HuzNA1 iii 6. ul-tu ul#-lu a-gu-gu-ma ina šub-[t]i-ia at-bu-ma aš₂-ku-na a-bu-bu
AššNA2 iii 8'. [x x x x x x x x x] šub#-ti-ia at-bu-ma aš₂-ku#-na* a-bu-bu
#note: Collation of the line in Lambert’s folio 18398.
BabLB1b iii? 3'. [x x x x x x x x x x x x a]-te-eb-bi-ma x [x x x x x]

#tr.en: “I arose from my residence, and the seams of heaven and earth were rent asunder.
133. %n ina šub[t]īya | atbē-ma | šipīt (|) šamê (|) (u) erṣeti | uptaṭṭir
#note: @akk{ši-BIT} is interpreted as @i{šipītu}, “seam” (following Landsberger’s proposal @i{apud} @bib{aro1958bemerkungen@25}, recommended also by @bib{RN1445@26}; on this word, see @bib{RN3043@225}, who advocates for a transcription with /@i{p}/). Compare the interpretation as @i{šipṭu}, “equilibrium,” in @bib{RN706@399b} and @bib{RN3209@155-156}. Compare also the understanding “Strafgericht Urteil” in @bib{hruška1974letzten@357 fn. 22}.
// cf. L I.5 SB "I" 170
// cf. L I.5 SB "II" 1
HuzNA1 iii 7. ina šub-[t]i-ia at-be₂-ma ši-pit AN#-e u KI-ti₃ up-ta-aṭ-ṭir
AššNA2 iii 9'. [x x x x x x x ši-pi]t AN-e KI-ti₃ up-ta-ṭir
BabLB1b iii? 4'. [x x x x x x x x x x x x K]I-ti₃ up-ta-a[ṭ-ṭi-ir]

#tr.en: “The heavens that were shaken: (for this cause,) the celestial bodies changed their positions, and I did not restore them to their places;
134. %n šamê | ša uštarʾibū | ša kakkabī (|) šamāmī | manzāssunu | išnī-ma | ul utīr | ašruššun
#note: Compare @bib{RN706@401a}: “Each of these difficult lines presents the same syntactic pattern: a relative clause without an antecedent acts as a casus pendens: «With reference to the quaking of the heavens(!) …, with reference to the shaking of the underworld …, with reference to the disturbing of the equilibrium of the universe …».”
// cf. L I.5 SB "IV" 123
