#tr.en: “I changed the location of the @i{mēsu}-tree (and its) amber, and revealed it to none.
148. %n ša mēsi (|) elmēši | ašaršun | unakkir-ma || ul ukallim | mamma
#note: The @i{mēsu}-tree is, as has been repeatedly observed (e.g. by @bib{RN1733@5-6} and @bib{schaudig_explaining_2019@382-383}, commonly mentioned in Mesopotamian literature as the preferred material for divine statues. The tree is commonly identified with the @i{Celtis australis} or hackberry tree on etymological grounds, but this identification does not fit the description of the tree in Mesopotamian sources particularly well (@bib{RN1953@17}).
NinNA3 iii 14'. [x x x x x x x x x x x x x x x x x x ma]m-ma
