#tr.en: “Who makes (it) shine like the noonday and places (it) at my feet?
157. %n ša kīma ūmi | ušanbaṭū-ma || (ina) šaplūʾa | ukann[u]
#note: The reading @akk{u₂-kan-[na-šu]} at the end of the line originates from a suggestion by von Soden (@i{apud} @bib{RN1811@15}). @bib{RN31@196} cautiously accepted this interpretation and compared it to the common Mesopotamian glyptic motif of a tree “bowed” under the feet of a god. The restoration is, however, highly improbable, as it would produce a non-trochaic ending (@i{ukannašu} being a subjunctive). Furthermore, MS TarNA1 appears to allow space for only one sign after @i{kan#}. The reading adopted here means that the object crafted by Ninildu is not Marduk’s statue but rather the pedestal upon which the statue rests. There is some evidence of wooden pedestals: for example, an inscription of Esarhaddon describes the reconstruction of the @i{šubat} @akk{{giš}}@i{musukkanni iṣi dārê} (“seat of @i{musukkannu}-wood, the everlasting wood”) of Tašmētu (@bib{RN393@Esarhaddon 48} r 91; see @bib{RN124@269}).
